      Algorithmic stablecoins
   =20
 =20
Here is how an algorithmic stablecoin works. You invent two tokens, call th=
em Dollarcoin and Sharecoin. You list them on the crypto exchanges. Shareco=
in trades for whatever price is determined by supply and demand. It might b=
e $0.01 per Sharecoin, or $1, or $100, who knows. But Dollarcoin is suppose=
d to trade at $1. If it trades at $0.99, you have some automatic process in=
 which you print more Sharecoins and use them to buy Dollarcoins until it i=
s back to $1. If it trades at $1.01, you have some automatic process in whi=
ch you print some more Dollarcoins and use them to buy Sharecoins until it =
is back to $1. The result is that Dollarcoin is firmly pegged to the dollar=
. The process is sometimes compared to algorithmic central banking, where t=
he central bank maintains the value of the currency (Dollarcoin) by adjusti=
ng its supply.On first principles this is insane. It relies on Sharecoin al=
ways being worth=C2=A0something. If Sharecoin trades at $0.01, you can prin=
t 10 million of them and buy 100,000 Dollarcoins and push the price up. But=
 if Sharecoin trades at $0.00, you can print infinity quadrillion of them a=
nd you=E2=80=99re still not gonna be able to push up the price of Dollarcoi=
n. If Sharecoin is worthless, it cannot be used to support the price of Dol=
larcoin. And because=C2=A0you just made it up, there is no particular reaso=
n for Sharecoin to be worth anything, so there is no particular reason for =
Dollarcoin to be worth a dollar. If=C2=A0I=C2=A0made up Sharecoin and Dolla=
rcoin on my computer and said to you =E2=80=9CI will give you the number 10=
 billion in this Excel spreadsheet if you give me=C2=A01 million U.S. dolla=
rs,=E2=80=9D you would say no, and if I raised my offer to 400 quadrillion =
you would not change your mind.On second principles, though, it=E2=80=99s f=
ine? I guess? Someone just made up Bitcoin, too, and it=E2=80=99s worth a l=
ot of money now. Also Dogecoin, etc. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll make up a digita=
l currency out of thin air and try to get people to buy it, and they=E2=80=
=99ll buy it and it will be an enduring store of value=E2=80=9D is now a pe=
rfectly plausible and repeatable proposition.You probably dress it up a bit=
. The way you dress it up will generally be with some sort of Ponzi-ing, be=
cause that is  the main way for self-contained crypto projects to create va=
lue=C2=A0these days. You say =E2=80=9Chey if you deposit Dollarcoins we=E2=
=80=99ll pay you a 20% yield in=C2=A0Sharecoins,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cif yo=
u stake Sharecoins we=E2=80=99ll give you a 20% yield in Sharecoins,=E2=80=
=9D or whatever, and the interest rate on this =E2=80=94=C2=A0the rate at w=
hich people are given new Sharecoins created out of thin air =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0is high enough that people get excited and do it for a trade, even if th=
ey understand that it=E2=80=99s all made up.The desired end state=C2=A0is, =
I think, that if you do this for like a decade and Dollarcoin becomes deepl=
y integrated into a booming crypto economy, then everyone just accepts that=
 it=E2=80=99s worth a dollar and you don=E2=80=99t have to work that hard t=
o defend the peg. And so Sharecoin also keeps its value and the whole syste=
m maintains itself. You Ponzi your way to widespread acceptance, and then y=
ou maintain the value mostly=C2=A0through the widespread acceptance, not th=
rough the algorithmic peg mechanism.On the other hand, this equilibrium=C2=
=A0feels=C2=A0quite unstable.=C2=A0Dollarcoin and Sharecoin are, in a funda=
mental way, correlated. One day people might wake up and say =E2=80=9Cwait=
=C2=A0you just=C2=A0made up this whole thing, what the heck, I am selling.=
=E2=80=9D And they=E2=80=99ll sell their Dollarcoins, driving down the pric=
e of Dollarcoin and requiring you to print more Sharecoins to defend the pe=
g, but they=E2=80=99ll also sell their Sharecoins, driving down the price o=
f Sharecoin and making it harder for you to defend the peg by printing Shar=
ecoins. And as the price of Sharecoin goes down and the peg gets less stabl=
e, more people will lose confidence and sell, making it harder to defend, e=
tc., in a self-reinforcing death spiral.This happens a lot! We talked last =
year about Titanium, a partially algorithmic stablecoin, which had itself a=
 nice death spiral.One way out of this is just to power through and hope fo=
r enduring widespread acceptance; if nobody attacks the peg you don=E2=80=
=99t have to defend it. But another way out is, once you have fairly good a=
cceptance and your tokens are worth a lot of money, you=C2=A0diversify=C2=
=A0the peg defense mechanism. Instead of saying =E2=80=9Cwe have a limitles=
s pool of entirely made-up Sharecoins, and we will spend Sharecoins to main=
tain the price of Dollarcoin at $1,=E2=80=9D you say =E2=80=9Cwe are a smal=
l country on the Continent of Crypto, and we have a central bank, and our c=
entral bank maintains foreign reserves, and we will spend those reserves to=
 maintain the price of Dollarcoin at $1.=E2=80=9D You print some Sharecoins=
 while the printing is good, you use them to buy like a billion dollars wor=
th of Bitcoin, and then if Dollarcoin goes to $0.99 you can spend some=C2=
=A0Bitcoins=C2=A0to buy Dollarcoin and push up the price.The advantage of t=
his is that Bitcoin is=C2=A0not=C2=A0correlated to your project, to Dollarc=
oin and Sharecoin. I mean, it probably is, both in the sense that=C2=A0Bitc=
oin, Dollarcoin and Sharecoin all reflect some general =E2=80=9Cfaith in cr=
ypto=E2=80=9D and in the sense that the more Bitcoin your project owns the =
more correlated you are to Bitcoin. But if people woke up tomorrow and said=
 =E2=80=9Cwait you just=C2=A0made up=C2=A0Dollarcoin and Sharecoin,=E2=80=
=9D they would not necessarily lose confidence=C2=A0in Bitcoin, because=C2=
=A0someone else=C2=A0made that up. Bitcoin is not an intrinsic part of your=
 project the way Dollarcoin and Sharecoin are, and your Bitcoin holdings wi=
ll maintain value in states of the world where Sharecoin does not. So you h=
ave more robust=C2=A0ammunition to defend the peg, so the peg is more robus=
t.And then you are off to the races, your Dollarcoin becomes more widely us=
ed, your Sharecoin=E2=80=99s price goes up, you use it to buy more Bitcoin =
and Ethereum and whatever else is good in crypto and eventually U.S. Treasu=
ries and gold bars and all the other stuff of central banking. And maybe on=
e day a Crypto George Soros attacks your peg and you have to spend a lot of=
 Bitcoin and gold defending it, and maybe you fail, but you are working wit=
h real tools instead of just stuff you made up. You used the stuff you made=
 up to buy the real tools.Here=E2=80=99s a good Wall Street Journal article=
 about algorithmic stablecoins:The esoteric topic of algorithmic stablecoin=
s has become more mainstream with the startling rise of TerraUSD, the most =
popular such coin. ...Here=E2=80=99s how TerraUSD works. If its price dips =
below $1, traders can =E2=80=9Cburn=E2=80=9D the coin=E2=80=94or permanentl=
y remove it from circulation=E2=80=94in exchange for $1 worth of new units =
of another cryptocurrency called Luna. That reduces the supply of TerraUSD =
and raises its price. Conversely, if TerraUSD climbs above $1, traders can =
burn Luna and create new TerraUSD. That increases supply of the stablecoin =
and lowers its price back toward $1.In other words, the collective efforts =
of traders seeking to make quick arbitrage profits should keep TerraUSD wit=
hin a relatively tight band around $1. Luna effectively acts as a shock abs=
orber for TerraUSD, buffering volatility in TerraUSD.Launched in 2020, Terr=
aUSD has mostly maintained its dollar peg=E2=80=94except during bouts of he=
avy volatility such as last spring=E2=80=99s big crypto selloff. TerraUSD d=
ropped below 92 cents on May 23, 2021, according to data provider CoinMarke=
tCap. =E2=80=A6TerraUSD is the brainchild of Do Kwon, a South Korean crypto=
 developer. A spokesman for Mr. Kwon=E2=80=99s company, Terraform Labs, sai=
d he was unavailable for an interview.=C2=A0During the past three months, M=
r. Kwon has sought to allay concerns about TerraUSD losing its peg by fundi=
ng a multibillion-dollar reserve of bitcoin and several other cryptocurrenc=
ies. The reserve is intended to act as an additional backstop against a sev=
ere drop in TerraUSD.=C2=A0Mr. Kwon has also argued that it is unlikely Ter=
raUSD=E2=80=99s liquidity will vanish because of all the activity on the co=
in from numerous trading and lending projects.See, one strategy is =E2=80=
=9Cpeople use it a lot so it will retain its value.=E2=80=9D The other stra=
tegy is, you build a reserve of stuff that you didn=E2=80=99t make up.Meanw=
hile at Bloomberg News, here=E2=80=99s  a profile of Kwon and Terra:Some li=
ken the seemingly too-good-to-be-true 20% interest on the Terra blockchain=
=E2=80=99s lending-and-borrowing program to one big Ponzi scheme that will =
ultimately collapse under its own weight. Others warn =E2=80=94 albeit with=
out much evidence =E2=80=94 that it risks bringing down the entire world of=
 digital assets.At the center of it all is Kwon, the 30-year-old =E2=80=9CK=
ing of the Lunatics.=E2=80=9D This year, a group led by Kwon wowed the lase=
r-eye crowd by buying more than $1.5 billion in Bitcoin to help prop up Ter=
ra, with plans to purchase as much as $10 billion worth of the token. That=
=E2=80=99s made it not only one of the original cryptocurrency=E2=80=99s bi=
ggest whales, but also a flash point for boosters and naysayers alike. Beli=
evers see the purchases as a bold move to bring Kwon=E2=80=99s vision a ste=
p closer to reality. Skeptics say it=E2=80=99s a desperate ploy to divert a=
ttention away from a project that=E2=80=99s bound to run out of money.=E2=
=80=9CRight now, my role in the crypto industry is a little polarizing,=E2=
=80=9D Kwon, co-founder of Terraform Labs, said in an interview with Bloomb=
erg. =E2=80=9CBecause, you know, we=E2=80=99ve been making a lot of big mov=
es. And that ruffles some feathers.=E2=80=9DThe basic structure of the trad=
e is (1) Ponzi, (2) acceptance, (3) diversification, (4) permanence. I feel=
 very dumb typing that! But I guess it works.
