   =20
      Twitter defense
   =20
 =20
We  talked yesterday about Twitter Inc.=E2=80=99s takeover defenses against=
 Elon Musk=E2=80=99s vague proposal to buy it. Or, rather, we talked about =
the poison pill that Twitter=E2=80=99s board of directors put in place to s=
top Musk. That=E2=80=99s the main takeover defense, in that it prevents Mus=
k from buying more shares without negotiating with the board. But Twitter i=
s actually pretty well defended against a hostile bid.In modern U.S. hostil=
e takeovers, the main way that a hostile bidder can fight back against a po=
ison pill goes like this:=09Launch a tender offer to buy 100% of the compan=
y=E2=80=99s stock directly from shareholders. The tender offer should be re=
al =E2=80=94=C2=A0with firm financing lined up =E2=80=94=C2=A0and fair to a=
ll shareholders. (It should be be for 100% of the stock, it should let ever=
yone get cash if they want, it should=C2=A0promise that if the bidder gets =
control of the company any second-step merger will be on the same terms, et=
c.) But the tender offer will be contingent on getting rid of the poison pi=
ll, which otherwise would make the bidder=E2=80=99s shares go poof; you can=
=E2=80=99t close the tender offer while the pill is in place.=09Launch a pr=
oxy fight to replace the board of directors who are standing in the way of =
the bid with some friendlier set of directors who will get rid of the pill =
and let the tender offer close.The tender offer asks shareholders to sell t=
heir shares to the bidder;=C2=A0the proxy fight=C2=A0asks shareholders to=
=C2=A0vote=C2=A0their shares first to get rid of the board and let the tend=
er offer close.Will Elon Musk do this? I dunno. There are two problems:=09T=
o launch a tender offer, he will need to write a detailed securities filing=
 committing him to buy the stock and detailing his plans and financing. If =
he has no financing and is just winging this, or if he doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0really=C2=A0want to buy all the stock, that will be hard.=09Twitter is s=
tructurally well protected from a proxy fight. It has a classified board, m=
eaning that only about one-third of directors are up for election at each a=
nnual meeting, so he can=E2=80=99t replace the whole board and get rid of t=
he pill. Also this year=E2=80=99s annual meeting is on May 25, he=E2=80=99s=
=C2=A0too late to run his own candidates, and Twitter=E2=80=99s charter doe=
sn=E2=80=99t allow shareholders to call special meetings to elect directors=
. So he won=E2=80=99t be able to get a majority of the board through proxy =
fighting until about 2024.Still he could gesture in that direction, if he w=
anted to. Bloomberg News  explains the situation:If Musk is serious about p=
ushing ahead with his takeover offer for Twitter, he should launch a tender=
 offer to acquire the shares in the company he doesn=E2=80=99t already own =
despite the poison pill, said Andrew Freedman, co-chair of the shareholder =
activism practice at law firm Olshan Frome Wolosky.=E2=80=9CEven though Mus=
k wouldn=E2=80=99t be able to close his tender offer, even with a majority =
of shares tendered, given the poison pill and other impediments, it=E2=80=
=99s a =E2=80=98put your money where your mouth is=E2=80=99 type move and s=
hows he really wants to buy this company,=E2=80=9D Freedman said.Musk could=
 simultaneously launch a proxy contest where he would ask shareholders to w=
ithhold their votes for the two directors who will stand for re-election at=
 this year=E2=80=99s annual meeting, which is slated for May 25, Freedman s=
aid. That would serve as a referendum on his offer, and also allow him to s=
olicit votes for an amendment to the company=E2=80=99s charter to declassif=
y the board, meaning that all directors would stand for election each year =
rather than just a few, he added. Last year, a similar proposal almost achi=
eved the 80% vote threshold required to change the company=E2=80=99s bylaws=
, he noted.If Musk doesn=E2=80=99t act in the next few months, he won=E2=80=
=99t be able to do much at Twitter until next year=E2=80=99s annual general=
 meeting because the company doesn=E2=80=99t allow for shareholders to call=
 a special meeting or act by written consent.=C2=A0Note that the =E2=80=9Cp=
roxy contest=E2=80=9D here would mostly symbolic, not about replacing the b=
oard so that he could do his deal but just about signaling to the board tha=
t shareholders=C2=A0want=C2=A0to let him do his deal. It is not particularl=
y clear to me that they do, but they might. And if the board got a strong s=
ignal that this is what shareholders want =E2=80=94=C2=A0from symbolic and =
structural votes at the annual meeting, or just from big shareholders calli=
ng the board to say =E2=80=9Cwe like Elon=E2=80=99s deal=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0it would not be=C2=A0obligated=C2=A0to take Musk=E2=80=99s deal, but =
it might feel some pressure to.=C2=A0A hostile takeover of Twitter is possi=
ble, but it would be a grinding drawn-out fight, and it=E2=80=99s possible =
that Musk would prefer to tweet mean things about the board rather than do =
the fighting.Elsewhere:=C2=A0Apollo Global Management Inc. is considering p=
articipating in a bid for Twitter Inc., according to people familiar with t=
he matter, after Elon Musk=E2=80=99s $43 billion bid put the social-media c=
ompany in play.Apollo, one of the world=E2=80=99s largest buyout firms, has=
 held discussions about backing a possible deal for Twitter and could provi=
de Mr. Musk or another bidder like private-equity firm Thoma Bravo LP with =
equity or debt to support an offer, the people said.Here is an estimate tha=
t Twitter could support  about $10 billion of debt, which is a little slim =
for a=C2=A0$40 billion or $50 billion buyout but is something at least. I s=
uppose there is some chance that if you lend to a Musk Twitter buyout, the =
cash flows won=E2=80=99t support the debt (especially after Musk removes co=
ntent moderation and advertisers leave), Musk will get bored, the debt will=
 default and you=E2=80=99ll end up owning Twitter for $10 billion. I=E2=80=
=99m not sure if you=E2=80=99d want that.
