   =20
      Short selling vs. suing
   =20
 =20
Conceptually, if a public company does a bad thing, or a bad thing happens =
to a public company, investors have two main ways to make money off of it:=
=09Sue for securities fraud or breach of fiduciary duty.=C2=A0Probably you =
need to have owned the company=E2=80=99s stock while it was doing the bad t=
hing if you want to take this approach, though if you are a big diversified=
 investor you probably did. The stock dropped when the bad thing became kno=
wn, you owned the stock, you were deceived, they should pay you.=09Sell the=
 company=E2=80=99s stock short, hoping to profit when the effects of the ba=
d thing are more widely known and the stock drops some more.But why not bot=
h? Here=E2=80=99s a  fun combination case:Two investment firms filed a clas=
s action suit against a telecom company, claiming investors were short-chan=
ged during its $3.1 billion sale. Then, the telecom company claims, they us=
ed the lawsuit as a kind of Trojan horse to gain access to confidential inf=
ormation, which helped them execute millions of dollars in short sales and =
other trades. =E2=80=A6IDT Corp. is the telecom company at the center of th=
e dispute, along with its spin-off Straight Path Communications Inc. Both w=
ere founded by serial entrepreneur Howard Jonas. Straight Path was run by J=
onas=E2=80=99s son Davidi prior to its sale to Verizon Communications Inc. =
in 2018.Basically Straight Path owed some money to the Federal Communicatio=
ns Commission, and there is a dispute about whether that money should have =
come out of the sale proceeds payable to=C2=A0its public shareholders (as h=
appened, and as IDT wants) or out of IDT (as the Straight Path investors wa=
nt). So some Straight Path shareholders, led by firms called JDS1 and The A=
rbitrage Fund,=C2=A0sued IDT for the money, about $600 million. If they win=
, they=E2=80=99ll get the $600 million, but also IDT will be out $600 milli=
on, which will probably be bad for its stock price. So they shorted some ID=
T too:That allegedly included shorting IDT=E2=80=99s stock beginning in Jul=
y 2017, as JDS1 and TAF were filing their complaints against IDT, and conti=
nuing in the months that followed as lawyers in the case were receiving con=
fidential information. (TAF itself is not alleged to have shorted IDT but i=
ts sister funds are, potentially making its status more difficult than JDS1=
=E2=80=99s for the court to untangle.)Jonas=E2=80=99s side argued that usin=
g confidential information obtained in the litigation to trade undermines t=
he class-action process.I mean, I guess. I have trouble getting mad at this=
? It just feels efficient, you know;=C2=A0they are using every part of the =
class-action process.
 =20
   =20
      The good trades are on Discord
   =20
 =20
Here=E2=80=99s a cool paper on =E2=80=9CSocial Media Group Investing,=E2=80=
=9D by Chaehyun Pyun of the University of Georgia:Online group discussions =
about stocks intensified after COVID-19, due to travel restrictions and sta=
y-at-home orders. Using data from investing-related chat rooms, I find that=
 live (synchronous) group chats help investors find high alpha stocks and a=
re more informative than individual posts and comments (asynchronous) in in=
vesting forums. Investor sentiment is less important than identifying which=
 stocks are currently most discussed, and they tilt towards small-cap and g=
rowth stocks. A popularity measure created using these stocks positively pr=
edicts future trading volume, stock volatility, and returns. Higher returns=
 are driven more by continued popularity than by sudden popularity. Taken t=
ogether, the results show how data from different social media platforms ma=
y have different market implications.The paper looks at something like 21,5=
00 investing-related Discord chat servers and finds that Discord=C2=A0inves=
tors seem to be=C2=A0actually picking good stocks, not just pumping bad one=
s:I also investigate two stories of channels in why more discussions may be=
 associated with increases in stock price. One possibility is that investor=
s understand what will happen to the cash flows of those most-mentioned com=
panies by doing some analysis, which is related to the informed trading exp=
lanation. The other possibility is that investors are pumping the stock, wh=
ich is related to the price pressure explanation. In other words, is the po=
pularity deserved or undeserved?To answer this question, my paper examines =
buy-and-hold returns over longer horizons and looks into insiders=E2=80=99 =
incentives and opportunities. Empirical results show that the buy-and-hold =
returns display a steady, continued upward drift over long horizons, provid=
ing empirical support for the informed trading explanation. Moreover, I fin=
d that insiders are less likely to sell shares after a stock becomes popula=
r, lending further support for informed discussions from a platform with li=
ve group chatting capability.Also that Discord is better at investing than =
Reddit:I choose Reddit WSB as the asynchronous platform since I find that i=
t shows a similar rise in users and the overall amount of chatter. The cumu=
lative portfolio returns show that the Discord EW portfolio outperforms the=
 S&P 500 and both Reddit WSB EW and VW portfolios, regardless of the portfo=
lio rebalancing frequency.Though Reddit is better at memes:I also find that=
 =E2=80=9Cmeme=E2=80=9D stocks like GameStop and AMC are mentioned more in =
Reddit than in Discord.These meme stocks also become one of the most discus=
sed stocks several months earlier in Reddit. For example, even though the o=
verall chatter on both platforms is similar in magnitude, GameStop was not =
a hot topic in Discord until the January 2021 short squeeze, while it was o=
ne of the most talked about stocks on Reddit since October 2020.I guess thi=
s is what you=E2=80=99d expect. There are lots of different Discord servers=
, some have waiting lists to join them, and it is a time commitment to sit =
around in a Discord chat all day; you are in some sense doing research. Whe=
reas you can just fire up Reddit, go to WallStreetBets, see the most popula=
r posts are about GameStop and go buy the most popular thing.
