10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Algorithmic stablecoins</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is how an algorithmic stablecoin =
works. You invent two tokens, call them Dollarcoin and Sharecoin. You list =
them on the crypto exchanges. Sharecoin trades for whatever price is determ=
ined by supply and demand. It might be $0.01 per Sharecoin, or $1, or $100,=
 who knows. But Dollarcoin is supposed to trade at $1. If it trades at $0.9=
9, you have some automatic process in which you print more Sharecoins and u=
se them to buy Dollarcoins until it is back to $1. If it trades at $1.01, y=
ou have some automatic process in which you print some more Dollarcoins and=
 use them to buy Sharecoins until it is back to $1. The result is that Doll=
arcoin is firmly pegged to the dollar. The process is sometimes compared to=
 algorithmic central banking, where the central bank maintains the value of=
 the currency (Dollarcoin) by adjusting its supply.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">On first principles this is insane. It relies on Sharecoin always =
being worth=C2=A0<em>something</em>. If Sharecoin trades at $0.01, you can =
print 10 million of them and buy 100,000 Dollarcoins and push the price up.=
 But if Sharecoin trades at $0.00, you can print infinity quadrillion of th=
em and you=E2=80=99re still not gonna be able to push up the price of Dolla=
rcoin. If Sharecoin is worthless, it cannot be used to support the price of=
 Dollarcoin. And because=C2=A0<em>you just made it up</em>, there is no par=
ticular reason for Sharecoin to be worth anything, so there is no particula=
r reason for Dollarcoin to be worth a dollar. If=C2=A0<em>I=C2=A0</em>made =
up Sharecoin and Dollarcoin on my computer and said to you =E2=80=9CI will =
give you the number 10 billion in this Excel spreadsheet if you give me=C2=
=A01 million U.S. dollars,=E2=80=9D you would say no, and if I raised my of=
fer to 400 quadrillion you would not change your mind.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">On second principles, though, it=E2=80=99s fine? I guess? Someo=
ne just made up Bitcoin, too, and it=E2=80=99s worth a lot of money now. Al=
so Dogecoin, etc. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll make up a digital currency out of t=
hin air and try to get people to buy it, and they=E2=80=99ll buy it and it =
will be an enduring store of value=E2=80=9D is now a perfectly plausible an=
d repeatable proposition.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You probably dres=
s it up a bit. The way you dress it up will generally be with some sort of =
Ponzi-ing, because that is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/27418577.257595/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydG=
ljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMjEvdGhlcmUtcy1pbnNpZGUtaW5mb3JtYXRpb24taW4tc2VjLWZpbGluZ=
3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQxOTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNl=
PW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNDE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB5ca4f57f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the main way</a> for self-contained c=
rypto projects to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
27418577.257595/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMjItMDEtMTkvd2FzaGluZy13ZWIzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MTkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZW=
RpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDQxOSZ1dG1fY2Ftc=
GFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3f9c8746" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">create val=
ue</a>=C2=A0these days. You say =E2=80=9Chey if you deposit Dollarcoins we=
=E2=80=99ll pay you a 20% yield in=C2=A0Sharecoins,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cif=
 you stake Sharecoins we=E2=80=99ll give you a 20% yield in Sharecoins,=E2=
=80=9D or whatever, and the interest rate on this =E2=80=94=C2=A0the rate a=
t which people are given new Sharecoins created out of thin air =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0is high enough that people get excited and do it for a trade, even if=
 they understand that it=E2=80=99s all made up.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The desired end state=C2=A0is, I think, that if you do this for like a=
 decade and Dollarcoin becomes deeply integrated into a booming crypto econ=
omy, then everyone just accepts that it=E2=80=99s worth a dollar and you do=
n=E2=80=99t have to work that hard to defend the peg. And so Sharecoin also=
 keeps its value and the whole system maintains itself. You Ponzi your way =
to widespread acceptance, and then you maintain the value mostly=C2=A0<em>t=
hrough the widespread acceptance</em>, not through the algorithmic peg mech=
anism.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, this equilibrium=
=C2=A0<em>feels=C2=A0</em>quite unstable.=C2=A0Dollarcoin and Sharecoin are=
, in a fundamental way, correlated. One day people might wake up and say =
=E2=80=9Cwait=C2=A0you just=C2=A0<em>made up</em> this whole thing, what th=
e heck, I am selling.=E2=80=9D And they=E2=80=99ll sell their Dollarcoins, =
driving down the price of Dollarcoin and requiring you to print more Sharec=
oins to defend the peg, but they=E2=80=99ll also sell their Sharecoins, dri=
ving down the price of Sharecoin and making it harder for you to defend the=
 peg by printing Sharecoins. And as the price of Sharecoin goes down and th=
e peg gets less stable, more people will lose confidence and sell, making i=
t harder to defend, etc., in a self-reinforcing death spiral.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This happens a lot! We talked last year <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27418577.257595/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTcvdGl0YW5pdW0tZ290LWN=
ydXNoZWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQxOTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc2=
91cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNDE5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf01c5832" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">about Titanium</a>, a partially =
algorithmic stablecoin, which had itself a nice death spiral.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way out of this is just to power through and hope =
for enduring widespread acceptance; if nobody attacks the peg you don=E2=80=
=99t have to defend it. But another way out is, once you have fairly good a=
cceptance and your tokens are worth a lot of money, you=C2=A0<em>diversify=
=C2=A0</em>the peg defense mechanism. Instead of saying =E2=80=9Cwe have a =
limitless pool of entirely made-up Sharecoins, and we will spend Sharecoins=
 to maintain the price of Dollarcoin at $1,=E2=80=9D you say =E2=80=9Cwe ar=
e a small country on the Continent of Crypto, and we have a central bank, a=
nd our central bank maintains foreign reserves, and we will spend those res=
erves to maintain the price of Dollarcoin at $1.=E2=80=9D You print some Sh=
arecoins while the printing is good, you use them to buy like a billion dol=
lars worth of Bitcoin, and then if Dollarcoin goes to $0.99 you can spend s=
ome=C2=A0<em>Bitcoins=C2=A0</em>to buy Dollarcoin and push up the price.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The advantage of this is that Bitcoin is=C2=
=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>correlated to your project, to Dollarcoin and Sharecoi=
n. I mean, it probably is, both in the sense that=C2=A0Bitcoin, Dollarcoin =
and Sharecoin all reflect some general =E2=80=9Cfaith in crypto=E2=80=9D an=
d in the sense that the more Bitcoin your project owns the more correlated =
you are to Bitcoin. But if people woke up tomorrow and said =E2=80=9Cwait y=
ou just=C2=A0<em>made up=C2=A0</em>Dollarcoin and Sharecoin,=E2=80=9D they =
would not necessarily lose confidence=C2=A0<em>in Bitcoin</em>, because=C2=
=A0<em>someone else=C2=A0</em>made that up. Bitcoin is not an intrinsic par=
t of your project the way Dollarcoin and Sharecoin are, and your Bitcoin ho=
ldings will maintain value in states of the world where Sharecoin does not.=
 So you have more robust=C2=A0ammunition to defend the peg, so the peg is m=
ore robust.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then you are off to the rac=
es, your Dollarcoin becomes more widely used, your Sharecoin=E2=80=99s pric=
e goes up, you use it to buy more Bitcoin and Ethereum and whatever else is=
 good in crypto and eventually U.S. Treasuries and gold bars and all the ot=
her stuff of central banking. And maybe one day a <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27418577.257595/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWE=
ub3JnL3dpa2kvQmxhY2tfV2VkbmVzZGF5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd9e60781" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">Crypto George Soros</a> attacks your peg and you have to spend a lot of B=
itcoin and gold defending it, and maybe you fail, but you are working with =
real tools instead of just stuff you made up. You used the stuff you made u=
p to buy the real tools.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a g=
ood <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27418577.25759=
5/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9jdXR0aW5nLWVkZ2UtY3J5cHRvLWNvaW5zL=
XRvdXQtc3RhYmlsaXR5LWNyaXRpY3MtY2FsbC10aGVtLWRhbmdlcm91cy0xMTY1MDIyNjU5Nz9t=
b2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15YWhvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0574178f" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Wall =
Street Journal article</a> about algorithmic stablecoins:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The esoteric topic of algorithmic stablecoins ha=
s become more mainstream with the startling rise of TerraUSD, the most popu=
lar such coin. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s how Terra=
USD works. If its price dips below $1, traders can =E2=80=9Cburn=E2=80=9D t=
he coin=E2=80=94or permanently remove it from circulation=E2=80=94in exchan=
ge for $1 worth of new units of another cryptocurrency called Luna. That re=
duces the supply of TerraUSD and raises its price. Conversely, if TerraUSD =
climbs above $1, traders can burn Luna and create new TerraUSD. That increa=
ses supply of the stablecoin and lowers its price back toward $1.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In other words, the collective efforts of traders se=
eking to make quick arbitrage profits should keep TerraUSD within a relativ=
ely tight band around $1. Luna effectively acts as a shock absorber for Ter=
raUSD, buffering volatility in TerraUSD.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">La=
unched in 2020, TerraUSD has mostly maintained its dollar peg=E2=80=94excep=
t during bouts of heavy volatility such as last spring=E2=80=99s big crypto=
 selloff. TerraUSD dropped below 92 cents on May 23, 2021, according to dat=
a provider CoinMarketCap. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">TerraUS=
D is the brainchild of Do Kwon, a South Korean crypto developer. A spokesma=
n for Mr. Kwon=E2=80=99s company, Terraform Labs, said he was unavailable f=
or an interview.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the past thre=
e months, Mr. Kwon has sought to allay concerns about TerraUSD losing its p=
eg by funding a multibillion-dollar reserve of bitcoin and several other cr=
yptocurrencies. The reserve is intended to act as an additional backstop ag=
ainst a severe drop in TerraUSD.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. =
Kwon has also argued that it is unlikely TerraUSD=E2=80=99s liquidity will =
vanish because of all the activity on the coin from numerous trading and le=
nding projects.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">See, one strat=
egy is =E2=80=9Cpeople use it a lot so it will retain its value.=E2=80=9D T=
he other strategy is, you build a reserve of stuff that you didn=E2=80=99t =
make up.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile at Bloomberg News, here=
=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2741857=
7.257595/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjItMDQtMT=
kvdGVycmFmb3JtLXMtZG8ta3dvbi1zLWh1Z2UtYml0Y29pbi1idXlzLWNhdGNoLWNyeXB0by1ia=
WxsaW9uYWlyZXMtYXR0ZW50aW9uP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MTkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRp=
dW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDQxOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGF=
pZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB40860a78" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a profile o=
f Kwon and Terra</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some like=
n the seemingly too-good-to-be-true 20% interest on the Terra blockchain=E2=
=80=99s lending-and-borrowing program to one big Ponzi scheme that will ult=
imately collapse under its own weight. Others warn =E2=80=94 albeit without=
 much evidence =E2=80=94 that it risks bringing down the entire world of di=
gital assets.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the center of it all is Kw=
on, the 30-year-old =E2=80=9CKing of the Lunatics.=E2=80=9D This year, a gr=
oup led by Kwon wowed the laser-eye crowd by buying more than $1.5 billion =
in Bitcoin to help prop up Terra, with plans to purchase as much as $10 bil=
lion worth of the token. That=E2=80=99s made it not only one of the origina=
l cryptocurrency=E2=80=99s biggest whales, but also a flash point for boost=
ers and naysayers alike. Believers see the purchases as a bold move to brin=
g Kwon=E2=80=99s vision a step closer to reality. Skeptics say it=E2=80=99s=
 a desperate ploy to divert attention away from a project that=E2=80=99s bo=
und to run out of money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CRight now=
, my role in the crypto industry is a little polarizing,=E2=80=9D Kwon, co-=
founder of Terraform Labs, said in an interview with Bloomberg. =E2=80=9CBe=
cause, you know, we=E2=80=99ve been making a lot of big moves. And that ruf=
fles some feathers.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">T=
he basic structure of the trade is (1) Ponzi, (2) acceptance, (3) diversifi=
cation, (4) permanence. I feel very dumb typing that! But I guess it works.=
</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" cellpaddin=
