<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Short selling vs. suing</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Conceptually, if a public company does=
 a bad thing, or a bad thing happens to a public company, investors have tw=
o main ways to make money off of it:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decim=
al; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">Sue for securities fraud or breach of fiduciary duty.=C2=A0Probably you =
need to have owned the company=E2=80=99s stock while it was doing the bad t=
hing if you want to take this approach, though if you are a big diversified=
 investor you probably did. The stock dropped when the bad thing became kno=
wn, you owned the stock, you were deceived, they should pay you.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sell the company=E2=80=99s stock short, hopi=
ng to profit when the effects of the bad thing are more widely known and th=
e stock drops some more.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But why not =
both? Here=E2=80=99s a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/27418577.257595/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjItMDQtMTgvc2hvcnQtc2VsbGVycy1hY2N1c2VkLW9mLXRyb2phbi1ob3JzZS1tYW5ldXZlc=
i1pbi1pbnZlc3Rvci1sYXdzdWl0P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MTkyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRp=
dW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDQxOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGF=
pZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5a19c052" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> fun combina=
tion case</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two investment f=
irms filed a class action suit against a telecom company, claiming investor=
s were short-changed during its $3.1 billion sale. Then, the telecom compan=
y claims, they used the lawsuit as a kind of Trojan horse to gain access to=
 confidential information, which helped them execute millions of dollars in=
 short sales and other trades. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">ID=
T Corp. is the telecom company at the center of the dispute, along with its=
 spin-off Straight Path Communications Inc. Both were founded by serial ent=
repreneur Howard Jonas. Straight Path was run by Jonas=E2=80=99s son Davidi=
 prior to its sale to Verizon Communications Inc. in 2018.</p></blockquote>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically Straight Path owed some money to the=
 Federal Communications Commission, and there is a dispute about whether th=
at money should have come out of the sale proceeds payable to=C2=A0its publ=
ic shareholders (as happened, and as IDT wants) or out of IDT (as the Strai=
ght Path investors want). So some Straight Path shareholders, led by firms =
called JDS1 and The Arbitrage Fund,=C2=A0sued IDT for the money, about $600=
 million. If they win, they=E2=80=99ll get the $600 million, but also IDT w=
ill be out $600 million, which will probably be bad for its stock price. So=
 they shorted some IDT too:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tha=
t allegedly included shorting IDT=E2=80=99s stock beginning in July 2017, a=
s JDS1 and TAF were filing their complaints against IDT, and continuing in =
the months that followed as lawyers in the case were receiving confidential=
 information. (TAF itself is not alleged to have shorted IDT but its sister=
 funds are, potentially making its status more difficult than JDS1=E2=80=99=
s for the court to untangle.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jonas=E2=80=
=99s side argued that using confidential information obtained in the litiga=
tion to trade undermines the class-action process.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, I guess. I have trouble getting mad at this? I=
t just feels efficient, you know;=C2=A0they are using every part of the cla=
ss-action process.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" c=
ellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">The good trades are on Discord</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a cool paper on =E2=80=
=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27418577.257595=
/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQwNT=
k2OTY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcb77668c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Social Media Group Inves=
ting</a>,=E2=80=9D by Chaehyun Pyun of the University of Georgia:</p><block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Online group discussions about stocks in=
tensified after COVID-19, due to travel restrictions and stay-at-home order=
s. Using data from investing-related chat rooms, I find that live (synchron=
ous) group chats help investors find high alpha stocks and are more informa=
tive than individual posts and comments (asynchronous) in investing forums.=
 Investor sentiment is less important than identifying which stocks are cur=
rently most discussed, and they tilt towards small-cap and growth stocks. A=
 popularity measure created using these stocks positively predicts future t=
rading volume, stock volatility, and returns. Higher returns are driven mor=
e by continued popularity than by sudden popularity. Taken together, the re=
sults show how data from different social media platforms may have differen=
t market implications.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The pap=
er looks at something like 21,500 investing-related Discord chat servers an=
d finds that Discord=C2=A0investors seem to be=C2=A0actually picking good s=
tocks, not just pumping bad ones:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">I also investigate two stories of channels in why more discussions may b=
e associated with increases in stock price. One possibility is that investo=
rs understand what will happen to the cash flows of those most-mentioned co=
mpanies by doing some analysis, which is related to the informed trading ex=
planation. The other possibility is that investors are pumping the stock, w=
hich is related to the price pressure explanation. In other words, is the p=
opularity deserved or undeserved?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To answer=
 this question, my paper examines buy-and-hold returns over longer horizons=
 and looks into insiders=E2=80=99 incentives and opportunities. Empirical r=
esults show that the buy-and-hold returns display a steady, continued upwar=
d drift over long horizons, providing empirical support for the informed tr=
ading explanation. Moreover, I find that insiders are less likely to sell s=
hares after a stock becomes popular, lending further support for informed d=
iscussions from a platform with live group chatting capability.</p></blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also that Discord is better at investing =
than Reddit:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I choose Reddit WS=
B as the asynchronous platform since I find that it shows a similar rise in=
 users and the overall amount of chatter. The cumulative portfolio returns =
show that the Discord EW portfolio outperforms the S&amp;P 500 and both Red=
dit WSB EW and VW portfolios, regardless of the portfolio rebalancing frequ=
ency.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Though Reddit is better =
at memes:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I also find that =E2=
=80=9Cmeme=E2=80=9D stocks like GameStop and AMC are mentioned more in Redd=
it than in Discord.These meme stocks also become one of the most discussed =
stocks several months earlier in Reddit. For example, even though the overa=
ll chatter on both platforms is similar in magnitude, GameStop was not a ho=
t topic in Discord until the January 2021 short squeeze, while it was one o=
f the most talked about stocks on Reddit since October 2020.</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess this is what you=E2=80=99d expect. T=
here are lots of different Discord servers, some have waiting lists to join=
 them, and it is a time commitment to sit around in a Discord chat all day;=
 you are in some sense doing research. Whereas you can just fire up Reddit,=
 go to WallStreetBets, see the most popular posts are about GameStop and go=
 buy the most popular thing.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" bord=
er=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
